column168: While in transit, (1) box containing (2) 1-gallon bottles of Blue Whale Muriatic Acid (UN1789) became crushed as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation. During the off-loading process, the damaged, crushed product began leaking onto the concrete dock floor; a total amount of 1-gallon. A Contractor neutralized the release using Kolorsafe Liquid Acid Neutralizer before absorbing the liquid and containerizing the spill debris into the proper UN-rated shipping container (a vented 55-gallon fiber drum). Additionally, the pallet in which the load was shipped on was also cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Lastly, the impacted box that the leaking bottles shipped in was neutralized and containerized for waste disposal. No storm drains, waterways, or soil were impacting by the release.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XRC experienced a UN2922 Thiocare H101 71% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4-gallons of product released to a 16’ x 18.5’ area of the trailer floor due to a crack in the tote lid. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Spill-X-A was utilized to neutralize the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted rags and PPE into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On 12/5/2023 at approximately 1326, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5190395 at the staion location in Miami, reporting an hazardous spill .  The shipment consists of a one fiberboard box classified as UN 3373, in which the inner container leaked due to a loose screw-on top.  The shipment suffered total loss and the shipper has been notified.  In compliance with 49 CFR 171.15, this incident was reported to the National Response Center and filed under report # 1385950.

While unloading a pallet of waste from a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility, a Veolia employee heard a pop and realized the forks on the forklift were protruding out of the back of the pallet and punctured a 15 gallon 1H1 drum of flammable liquid located on the pallet behind the one he was moving. Approximately 100 ml of the material leaked out before the hole closed on itself. The employee moved the forklift away from the area and shut it off, then proceeded to contain the spill with absorbent. The employee and the Veolia site manager then donned correct PPE and promptly overpacked the container and cleaned up the spill area.
column169: The Veolia employee needs to be aware of the length of their forks on the forklift in reference to the material they are handling and ensure that their forks do not protrude out the back of the pallet they are working on. Also whenever possible use a spotter to ensure safe loading practices.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LLA experienced a UN1866 ELAN-Cast P 300 S RTC Low Odor release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of material released to the entire trailer floor as well as a 30’ x 20’ area of the concrete lot below due to the trailer wall puncturing the tote. The puncture was patched with wood to stop the release and the material was transferred into a new tote for shipment on. The free-standing liquid material was collected with a drum vac into (2) 55-gallon metal drums. Floor dry was then deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into a third 55-gallon metal drum. The punctured tote was patched with absorbent pads & chemical tape. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
While loading (1) -(55) gal plastic drum was punctured by a forklift employee.

column168: XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal URD. column168: On December 1, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2735 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Enviro Care, Inc. (EC) to remediate the impacted site. EV personnel deployed absorbents to the release and utilized hand tools to remediate the site. The crew containerized the one (1) damaged 55-gallon drum in one (1) 95-gallon overpack. All UN2735-impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum and one (1) cubic yard bag for future disposal.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: On December 1, 2023, two (2) 55-gallon drums of UN3265 were punctured by a forklift and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the release and worked them in with hand tools. All UN3265-impacted material was containerized in three (3) 55-galon drums. The two (2) damaged 55-gallon drums were overpacked into two (2) 95-gallon overpacks for terminal disposal.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: On December 4, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1230 was punctured and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Patriot Environmental Services (PES) to remediate the site.  PES personnel deployed granular absorbents to the methanol-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. Crews transferred the product into a new 330-gallon tote.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: On December 4, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2031 had a faulty cap in transit and leaked approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the top and sides of drum, as well as the poly wrap. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GMES) to remediate the impacted site.  GMES personnel removed all contaminated poly wrap to inspect the drum. Crews utilized rags and a neutralizing solution to collect the released product from the top and sides of the drum. GMES personnel utilized an 85-gallon open top drum to overpack and contain the damaged 55-gallon drum. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 30-gallon drum. All containers were staged onsite for future disposal.

column168: SequenceEvent: The package was brought to our attention from just the smell alone. column168: SequenceEvent: came off of trailer, brought to QA, Cleaned up. DescribePack: Loose caps, and internal leakage. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: tighten caps, put in red hazmat tote and bag.

SequenceEvent: The package was pulled off the trailer and the bottom of the box was damp. Upon discovery that it was a hazmat package, it was removed from the sort, placed in a lined hazmat tote and taken to the hazmat cage to be held for inspection. DescribePack: On inspection, 4 4 liter glass jugs were found, 1 of which had no lid in place. Visual inspection determined that approximately .5 liters had leaked out of the jug and into the box, soaking into the corrugated inner liner and the bottom of the box. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: Removed the package from the sort, to prevent leakage onto other packages, placed it in a lined hazmat tote and placed it in the hazmat cage for inspection.

SequenceEvent: The driver that had this package on his truck was out delivering when he discovered the leaking hazmat. He put the package in plastic bags to try to contain the spill. He promptly drove to back to the Fedex Ground station and alerted QA of the package. The driver pulled the package out causing some to spill on a few other packages in the truck. He set the package on the passenger side steps while QA investigated. One QA person called the emergency number who stated they could someone out to clean up or we could clean up if we felt we could handle it. QA placed the package in a red hazmat tote. QA sprinkled the area with neutralizing powder as a safety measure. The spill was soaked up and the clean up materials placed in the salvage drum. DescribePack: The top of the cap on the bottle has broken off. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a lined red hazmat tote and put into a well ventilated area. Absorbent pads were placed on the area of the spill that appeared to be dry already. We sprinkled neutralizing powder on the area just in case. The steps of the truck where the hazmat had been placed were wet so we sprinkled the neutralizing powder there as well.
